EON, Hartalega, Shell, Hong Leong Bank: Malaysia Equity Preview

-- B y   C h a n   T i e n   H i n
-- 
2011-05-11T00:36:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-11/eon-hartalega-shell-hong-leong-bank-malaysia-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in Malaysia trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the previous close, unless
stated otherwise.  The  FTSE Bursa Malaysia KLCI (FBMKLCI)  Index rose 0.3 percent to
1,523.37.  EON Capital Bhd. (EON)  : The bank’s first-quarter profit
gained 25 percent from a year earlier to 122.2 million ringgit
($41 million) as net interest income increased, according to a
company statement. EON slid 0.3 percent to 7.52 ringgit.        Hartalega Holdings Bhd. (HART)  : The Malaysian producer
of synthetic and latex gloves said profit for the fourth quarter
ended March 31 rose 13 percent from a year earlier to 52.4
million ringgit as sales climbed, according to a company
statement. The stock was unchanged at 5.70 ringgit.  Hong Leong Bank Bhd. (HLBK)  : The banking group plans to
increase the size of its rights offer to as much as 2.6 billion
ringgit from 1.6 billion ringgit to strengthen its capital base
and fund working capital, according to a company statement. Hong
Leong also said profit for the third quarter ended March 31
climbed 27 percent from a year earlier to 289.7 million ringgit.
The stock gained 2.7 percent to 11.50 ringgit.        Hong Leong Financial Group Bhd. (HLFG)  : The banking and
insurance group’s net income in the third quarter ended March 31
surged 86 percent from a year earlier to 264.6 million ringgit
as revenue increased, according to a company statement. The
company also proposed a second interim dividend of 15 sen a
share and a special dividend of 3 sen a share, it said. The
stock gained 3.3 percent to 11.14 ringgit.  Shell Refining Co. (SHELL MK): The Malaysian unit of Royal
Dutch Shell Plc said first-quarter net income more than doubled
from a year earlier to 135.5 million ringgit as revenue gained,
according to a stock exchange filing. The stock fell 0.4 percent
to 10.84 ringgit.        UOA Real Estate Investment Trust (UOAR)  : The property
trust said first-quarter net income rose 73 percent from a year
earlier to 11.6 million ringgit, according to a company
statement. The stock was unchanged at 1.40 ringgit.  Mulpha International Bhd. (MIT)  : The property developer
proposed a dividend reinvestment plan that would allow
shareholders to reinvest their dividends in new shares. This is
to boost  shareholder value , the company said in a stock filing.
The shares were unchanged at 50 sen.  To contact the reporter on this story:
